CONTEXTIQ — MASTER ARCHITECTURE DOCUMENT

SECTION 1 — SYSTEM OVERVIEW
ContextIQ is a Decision Intelligence and Commitment Governance platform. It ingests organisational email communications, extracts commitments, detects contradictions, tracks commitment evolution over time, and reconstructs the full context behind any business decision — automatically, from existing communication without requiring any manual data entry.
It is not an email assistant. It is not a summarisation tool. It is an organisational memory and accountability system built on top of communication infrastructure that already exists.
Target deployment — Azure cloud, Microsoft ecosystem, financial services and enterprise organisations.
Target users — project managers, compliance officers, senior leadership, audit teams, operations teams in mid to large enterprises.

SECTION 2 — HIGH LEVEL ARCHITECTURE
ContextIQ has six layers. Every component sits in exactly one layer. Data flows downward through layers. Intelligence flows upward.
Layer 1 — Communication Layer. Microsoft Outlook mailboxes. Source of all data. ContextIQ never modifies anything here.
Layer 2 — Ingestion Layer. Microsoft Graph API integration. Pulls emails, cleans them, pseudonymises PII, stores in operational database. Component 0 lives here.
Layer 3 — Intelligence Layer. Commitment extraction, contradiction detection, lineage tracking. Components 1, 2, 3 live here. Writes to both PostgreSQL and Neo4j simultaneously.
Layer 4 — Reasoning Layer. Context reconstruction, hybrid RAG pipeline, knowledge graph traversal. Component 4 lives here. Reads from PostgreSQL, Neo4j, and pgvector. Writes answers to cache.
Layer 5 — Analytics Layer. Commitment risk scoring, stakeholder accountability mapping. Components 5 and 6 live here. Read from all stores, produce aggregate intelligence.
Layer 6 — Presentation Layer. REST API, web UI, alert system. What users actually interact with. Enforces RBAC at every request.

SECTION 3 — DATA ARCHITECTURE
SUBSECTION 3A — POSTGRESQL WITH PGVECTOR
Primary operational database. Stores all structured data. pgvector extension handles vector storage and similarity search co-located with relational data.
Connection management — use PgBouncer for connection pooling. PgBouncer sits between your application and PostgreSQL, managing a pool of database connections efficiently. Without it, each application request opens a new database connection — expensive and slow under load. With PgBouncer, connections are reused. Add PgBouncer to your tech stack.
Schema organisation — three separate PostgreSQL schemas.
Schema 1 — core. All main operational tables. Accessible by application layer with appropriate RBAC filtering.
Schema 2 — security. PII vault, audit log, consent records. Accessible only by security service and workspace admins. Strict row level security policies enforced at PostgreSQL level using PostgreSQL's built in row level security — RLS. This means even if application code has a bug that tries to access another workspace's PII, PostgreSQL itself blocks it.
Schema 3 — analytics. Aggregated metrics, cached query results, cost tracking. Readable by analytics layer, writable only by background jobs.
