SECTION 10 — GMAIL EXTENSIBILITY — ADAPTER PATTERN
Your EmailProvider abstract base class defines the interface —
fetch_messages method. Parameters — since_timestamp, max_results. Returns list of standardised EmailMessage objects.

get_thread method. Parameters — thread_id. Returns standardised EmailThread object.

mark_processed method. Parameters — message_id. Returns boolean.

get_delta method. Parameters — delta_token. Returns new messages and new delta token.
OutlookProvider implements EmailProvider using Microsoft Graph API and MSAL.
GmailProvider would implement EmailProvider using Google Gmail API and Google OAuth. Same interface, different implementation. Zero changes to any other component.
Standardised EmailMessage object — message_id, thread_id, sender_email, sender_name, recipients, cc, body_raw, sent_at, source_provider. The source_provider field records whether this came from Outlook or Gmail for audit purposes.
When an interviewer asks — "can this support Gmail?" — you say "Yes. I implemented the Adapter Pattern with an abstract EmailProvider interface. Adding Gmail support means writing a GmailProvider class that implements the same interface using Google's Gmail API. Every component above the ingestion layer is completely unaware of which email provider is being used. The switch is one line of configuration."

SECTION 11 — DEPLOYMENT ARCHITECTURE
Three environments — development, staging, production.
Development — local Docker Compose. All services — FastAPI, PostgreSQL, Neo4j, Redis, Celery — run locally in containers. No Azure costs during development.
Staging — Azure Kubernetes Service with reduced resource allocation. Mirrors production architecture. Used for integration testing and change management validation.
Production — Azure Kubernetes Service with full resource allocation. Auto scaling enabled. Azure managed services for PostgreSQL, Redis. Neo4j on Azure VM with managed disk encryption.
CI/CD pipeline — GitHub Actions. On every pull request — run full test suite, run LLM evaluation on test dataset, check code coverage above 80 percent. On merge to main — build Docker image, push to Azure Container Registry, deploy to staging automatically, require manual approval for production deployment.
